{
  // Outfit Reactions - editable prompt style blocks.
  // Keep every key and placeholder. Missing or invalid values use built-in defaults.

  "HairChangeMode": "The NPC noticed the farmer's hairstyle or hair color changed. IMPORTANT: only the hairstyle or hair color is new; the farmer's outfit is exactly the same as before. React to the hair change and how it affects the farmer's overall vibe. Name exact colors or specific hairstyles only when the support data makes them clear.",
  "HatChangeMode": "The NPC noticed the farmer's head item or headwear. React to what it seems to be and how it changes the farmer's vibe. Do not call small headbands, tiaras, bows, flowers, clips, or hair accessories a hat unless the support data says it is a hat.",
  "AccessoryChangeMode": "The NPC noticed the farmer's accessory changed. IMPORTANT: only the accessory is new; the farmer's outfit and hairstyle are unchanged. React naturally to the accessory and how it pairs with the current outfit. A funny, cute, ugly, strange, dramatic, or impossible combination may be compared, questioned, teased, or turned into an in-world joke. If the accessory is visually unclear, do not guess.",
  "OutfitChangeMode": "The NPC noticed the farmer's saved outfit. React naturally to what it seems to be, the situation, any recognizable theme or reference, and the farmer's overall vibe. Mention colors, texture, or style only as small character-specific details, not as a fashion review.",

  "NaturalReactionStyle": "React to the farmer's {Change} through the NPC's established personality and relationship. {OutfitFocusRule}Use location, season, weather, time, and privacy only when they create a meaningful human reaction, never as a forced closing justification. For head items, respect the equipped and support data: a headband, tiara, bow, clip, flower, pin, or crown is not automatically a hat.",

  "PlayerKnownAddressRule": "PLAYER ADDRESS RULE: the player character's name is {PlayerName}. When direct address is useful, prefer the player's name over a generic role label. Do not address the player as a localized equivalent of 'farmer', 'player', 'rancher', 'new farmer', or 'newcomer' when the NPC would reasonably know their name. Role or job words may describe farm work, but must not replace the player's name. FARM NAMING RULE: when referring to the player's agricultural property, use the standard direct equivalent of 'farm' in {TargetLanguage}. Do not substitute a term whose ordinary meaning is countryside, a rural region, ranch, homestead, smallholding, fields, or subsistence plot. Use the player's name sparingly and only when it serves a genuine conversational purpose.",
  "PlayerUnknownAddressRule": "PLAYER ADDRESS RULE: the player character's name is unavailable. Avoid overusing generic role labels as direct address; use natural dialogue without a vocative when possible. FARM NAMING RULE: when referring to the player's agricultural property, use the standard direct equivalent of 'farm' in {TargetLanguage}. Do not substitute a term whose ordinary meaning is countryside, a rural region, ranch, homestead, smallholding, fields, or subsistence plot.",
  "PlayerGenderRule": "PLAYER GENDER RULE: the player character's grammatical gender is {PlayerGender}. Use matching grammatical agreement in {TargetLanguage} when the language requires gendered pronouns, adjectives, nouns, or titles. If grammatical gender is unnecessary in that sentence, neutral wording is allowed. Do not add gendered labels unnecessarily. {GenderSpecificCaution}",

  "VisibleVanillaHatOnlyMode": "HAT-ONLY reaction mode: react exclusively to the visible vanilla or base-game hat the farmer is wearing. Focus on the hat itself, its look, shape, color, vibe, and how it suits or clashes with the farmer. Do not mention or factor in clothes, other accessories, hair, or the rest of the outfit.",
  "RemovedVanillaHatOnlyMode": "HAT-REMOVAL-ONLY reaction mode: the farmer just removed a vanilla or base-game hat and this NPC has enough prior context to notice. The farmer is currently bare-headed. React only to the removal or absence of the hat. Do not imply a hat is still being worn, invent current hat details, or shift focus to the rest of the outfit.",

  "SavedOutfitFocusGuidance": "Focus guidance: the NPC noticed the saved outfit. React first to what it seems to be, any recognizable theme or reference, the situation, and the farmer's overall vibe. Humor, questions, playful roasting, imagined scenarios, and character-specific comparisons are valid. Mention colors or details only when supported and natural. Do not center hair, hair color, or a tiny generic head-slot item unless it clearly completes the outfit.",
  "HairFocusGuidance": "Focus guidance: the NPC noticed the hairstyle or hair change. Name a hair color only when support data confirms it, and use that exact broad color. Never infer hair color from pixels, lighting, scenery, or the background. Name a specific hairstyle only when unmistakably clear; otherwise refer generally to the new hairstyle or look. A large obvious accessory may be secondary context, but do not ignore the hair change.",
  "HatFocusGuidance": "Focus guidance: the NPC noticed the hat or headwear change. Weave it naturally into the overall look without letting unrelated details take over. Name a headwear color only when support data confirms it. Describe shape or style only when visually clear; otherwise refer to it generally.",
  "AccessoryFocusGuidance": "Focus guidance: the NPC noticed a Fashion Sense accessory change. Focus on a clearly visible accessory, but consider it together with the current saved outfit or theme. The NPC may react to a fitting combination, funny mismatch, cute chaos, weird hybrid, dramatic upgrade, ugly clash, or another in-character effect. Ignore makeup-like or visually unclear accessories instead of guessing.",

  "FashionSenseVisualSupportRule": "Fashion Sense support data is authoritative for equipped item IDs and any confirmed hair or headwear color it explicitly states. The attached image may supply only clear broad clothing or outfit colors. Never take outfit colors from hair, tiny head pieces, floor, background, scenery, lighting, furniture, or walls. Ignore generic or internal item IDs as dialogue content. Never mention Fashion Sense, APIs, filenames, IDs, or technical labels. Current equipped visual data: {VisualSummary}",
  "FashionSenseVisualSeparationRule": "The hair entry is the farmer's hairstyle, not a hat or part of the outfit palette. Clearly visible large accessories may count as part of the overall look; makeup-like or unclear accessories should not. For a whole-outfit reaction, never infer hair or headwear colors from pixels. If a generic head-slot item is visually unclear, ignore it instead of guessing.",
  "SpecialItemVisibleRule": "SPECIAL ITEM REACTION DATA. This is authoritative for the item the farmer is currently wearing. Do not mention technical labels, JSON keys, or internal data sources in dialogue: {SpecialItemData}\nUse this as a high-priority reaction hook according to the NPC's personality, relationship, and current context, especially any NPC-specific instruction or secret-knowledge boundary in the data.",
  "SpecialItemRemovedRule": "SPECIAL ITEM JUST REMOVED. The farmer was wearing a special item and has now taken it off. React to the fact that it is gone based on how this NPC feels about that item. Data: {SpecialItemData}",
  "SpecialItemMemoryRule": "MEMORY - IMPORTANT: {ItemMemory}\nThe NPC already has history with this exact item. Do not write the line as a first-time discovery. Show familiarity, recall it naturally, or express an established opinion in the NPC's own voice.",
  "SpecialVanillaHatRule": "SPECIAL VANILLA HAT REACTION DATA. This is authoritative for the currently equipped vanilla or base-game hat: {SpecialHatData}\nDo not mention technical labels, JSON keys, categories, tags, or source files. Use the hat as a high-priority appearance hook and react according to the NPC's personality, relationship, location, season, and context rather than defaulting to generic praise.",
  "VanillaHatMemoryRule": "MEMORY - IMPORTANT: {HatMemory}\nThe NPC already has history with this exact hat. Weave that recognition into the reaction in the NPC's own voice and do not write it as a first-time discovery.",

  "ReactionCoreRule": "React directly to the farmer's current appearance, visible theme, situation, or overall vibe. Choose a concrete in-character reaction angle; mention visual details only when natural and never structure the line like a fashion review.",
  "ThemeRecognitionRule": "When a clear clue points to a recognizable character, franchise, mascot, creature, animal, food, object, or named style, let the NPC recognize or allude to it only when their knowledge and personality support that. Do not force uncertain recognition or ignore an obvious clue. Prefer a fitting joke, question, roast, concern, guarded admission, or imagined situation over bland praise, and draw comparisons from this NPC's own interests rather than generic Stardew topics.",
  "CombinationAndOccasionRule": "Consider a changed item together with any recognizable outfit still being worn, including fitting combinations, clashes, or funny hybrids. Judge clear event-specific clothing against the current place, active festival, season, weather, and time. A clear mismatch may be questioned or teased in character; never force an ambiguous comparison or call a fitting occasion mismatched.",
  "WholeOutfitFocusRule": "For a whole saved outfit, react to the complete look. Do not center hair, hair color, a tiny head-slot item, or a generic or internal item ID unless the theme truly revolves around it.",
  "OpeningVarietyRule": "OPENING VARIETY RULE: vary the first words, sentence structure, and reaction angle. Do not repeatedly begin with equivalents of 'this look or outfit', generic greetings, grunts, or 'what are you wearing?', and do not make 'it suits you' the main point. Start naturally from this NPC's observation, joke, complaint, concern, question, or admission.",
  "DialoguePacingRule": "Use #$b# dialogue-box breaks only when they improve natural pacing. One, two, or several boxes are valid; never force a fixed box count, pad the line, or repeat an idea just to make it longer.",
  "ExpressiveCuesAllowedRule": "Brief expressive cues in asterisks are allowed when they fit the character and moment. Write them in the same language as the dialogue and never use asterisks as list bullets.",
  "ExpressiveCuesDisabledRule": "Do not use asterisks for actions or physical cues. Write only clean spoken dialogue.",
  "PunctuationRule": "Punctuation rule: use '...' for dramatic pauses, hesitation, trailing off, or unfinished thoughts; never use a lone period as a pause inside a sentence.",
  "IndoorWeatherRule": "Weather and location rule: the NPC and farmer are indoors and sheltered. Rain, storms, snow, or similar weather is outside, never happening inside the room. Mention it only when it naturally matters.",
  "OutdoorWeatherRule": "Weather and location rule: the NPC and farmer are outdoors and directly exposed to the stated weather. It may be described as happening around them when relevant.",
  "ActiveFestivalPresenceRule": "ACTIVE FESTIVAL RIGHT NOW, authoritative live event: {ActiveFestivalName}. The farmer and speaking NPC are physically attending it together in the current location. This overrides ambiguity from a generic map name.",
  "ActiveFestivalOutfitRule": "ACTIVE-FESTIVAL OUTFIT RULE: compare any clear costume, holiday, seasonal, or festival theme with {ActiveFestivalName}. If it fits, treat it as timely. If it clearly belongs to another festival, holiday, season, or occasion, the NPC must notice the mismatch in character. Never say the active festival passed, is upcoming, happens next year, or is not taking place; never substitute a different real-world holiday. Do not force a festival comparison for an ambiguous look."
}
